  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a real and deeply felt phenomenon that I’ve observed throughout my life, especially in the classrooms and labs where I once taught and where I’ve seen my children grow. It’s the anxiety that arises when individuals, particularly women and people of color, fear their performance might confirm negative stereotypes about their group. For instance, when a girl in my daughter’s school class is told she’s ‘not a math person,’ or when a Black student hesitates to ask questions in a physics class because they worry about being labeled as ‘less capable,’ this isn’t just a minor worry—it’s a barrier to learning and participation. As a retired educator with a background in upper secondary education, I’ve seen how this fear can lead to underperformance, even among bright students who otherwise have the talent and drive. The question of whether we should address it is not just a yes or no—it’s a critical necessity. We must do so through subtle, consistent efforts that build trust and normalize diversity in STEM fields. This means creating inclusive environments where every student feels safe to explore their interests without fear of judgment. I’ve found that mentorship programs, where students are paired with role models who share their backgrounds, have been particularly effective. Also, integrating stories of diverse scientists into curricula helps dismantle the myth that STEM is for only a select few. The key is to approach this not as a problem to be fixed overnight but as a gradual, patient process that requires empathy and sustained commitment. In my own life, I’ve struggled with depression, which has made me more attuned to the emotional toll of such stereotypes. I believe that addressing stereotype threat isn’t just about improving academic outcomes—it’s about fostering a sense of belonging that can transform lives and communities.",
